title: 6-Pin or 10-Pin Shrouded Male Connector - IDC - Printable

description.text: This is a 6-Pin Shrouded Male Connector which accepts an IDC Connector. I bought some Polulu Carrier kits and only a 10-Pin Connector was included. Unfortunately, I don't have any electronics suppliers in my town and I didn't want to wait for a delivery, so I built my own. Update: Openscad Parametric Version coming soon. I keep meaning to learn some OpenScad so I can easily make these types of things parametric, but every time I start, I end up thinking, "Man I could get this done in like 20 seconds in Sketchup".

Pictures on the left kind of show you what to glue where. It is pretty obvious but I posted them just in case. Noticed that some people are printing these and end up with walls that don't get filled. This is an issue with the 'extra shells' options in Skeinforge. For some reason skeinforge has trouble with small or thin objects when you have extra shells turned on. To fix this issue, set the three 'extra shells' options to 0 in the 'fill' plugin. This 'bug?!' may be fixed soon, I don't know, but it is confirmed to exist all the way up to the current version SF40 I believe. Print the part. Get an IDC connector and stick 3 x 2 male header pins in it (picture 1). I used one with a broken clip for testing purposes just in case I was sloppy with the glue. Surround the walls of the opening in the bottom of the printed connector shroud with some ABS cement (Picture 2)(I use Plastruct Plastic Weld, which you can get in just about any hobby shop). Stick your IDC connector with the male header pins into the hole. Wait for the ABS Cement to set. I also put glue across the bottom of the assembled shroud, to get better adhesion (picture 3). Remove the IDC connector once you are sure the cement has set. And you should now have an Assembled 6 Pin Shrouded Male Connector for your Electronics Projects!

description.text:

Mine has a DC jack so I can plug in an AC adapter anywhere from 6 to 12V and run it.  I plan to run the prototype in my window rotating my kid's Chiapet running off of a solar panel.  
Would like to add a speed control POT before I finish it so you can adjust the rotation speed from super slow to slow.

description.text:
I have created a device which allows people who need to use syringes in there day to day life's to be able to do so safely. This design allows you to safely remove the cap of a syringe using the clamp feature and lets you put the cap back onto the syringe.  
The regulations state that you must be able to put the cap back on a syringe using only 1 hand to ensure you don't accidentally stab your self.  
Taking the cap off the syringe does require the use of 2 hand but one hand is used to clamp the cap while you use the other hand to pull the syringe out of the cap.  
When taking the cap off, put the end of the cap under the first lip of the product, then clamp the cap into place using the clamp feature, this way it will make sure you get a good grip and the cap won't slip. The product will fit any length cap short or long because of the hole at the bottom of the product.  
Please take great care using this design!

title: Bose Soundlink Mini Phone/Tablet Holder Wire mount

description.text:
Holds your phone or tablet on top of your Bose SoundLink Mini speaker, inner width is adjustable between 95mm and 155mm by sliding the holders left and right.  
Mount them from the left and right outermost top. They should fit if you hook in the backside and gently pinch the top.  
Don't force them around the corners as they might cosmetically damage your rubbers between the speaker grill and enclosure.  
Depending on your tolerances it is important to note i made an effort to exclude the speaker grill and rubber from any friction, you might need to remove material to make sure it only runs on outer rim of the aluminum casing and only touches the rubber when moving upwards.

Inspired by the Bq Ciclop and the B.Owens Piclop, I have begun my re-mix of this project combining the framework of the Ciclop printed pieces and the work others have done in utilizing the Raspberry Pi to drive this scanner. I'm also re-mixing other peoples work (credit given by listing them as sources). Any re-worked STL's I'll include in this project here. The rest of the source files for those looking for them will have to go to the respective sources. I've set up a blog to record my successes (and hopefully not too many failures) of this project. http://cicloppi.blogspot.ca/ My goal is to re-mix a bunch of pieces found here on Thingiverse (noted in the re-mixed from links) along with some ideas and designs of my own hopefully in the end resulting in a functional Ciclop Pi Edition... The plan is to use this space to hold all of the printable pieces for those interested in downloading them. My blog (noted above) will contain progress reports. May 23rd, 2015 Update:
Managed to get a little time to start putting it together. Starting to look like a scanner. I decided to re-print the tower in white (as you can see in the photos), and at the same time remove the internal support structure for holding the Ciclop circuit board, also dropped the inside bottom a little to give a bit more overall space in the tower for electronics. Next will be to finish building the big bearing (no, I'm not planning on buying that bearing, going to try to print my own). Then continue on with the build. STL Descriptions: Piclop Plate
Built this to provide some extra bolting strength to the base of the Ciclop camera tower Top Plug
This fits in to block off the Logitech camera location at the top of the Ciclop camera tower. This piece is a work-in-progress, destined to become part of the camera Raspberry Pi camera mount for the factory Ciclop tower. Motor Tube Double Long
This is a Re-mix of the Faan P "Piclop Laser Scanner" motor tube such that in this STL, it is twice as long as the one provided in his build. That way I don't have to stack two of them between the motor base and the tower, I can just print a single. Be fore-warned, you'll need something equivalent to the TAZ5 build volume to pull that one off.

This is a shadow the largest of the 6 regular polytopes in 4D. It is made from 600 tetrahedra. This is the dual of the 120 cell. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20788
Unlike the other 4D shadows that I have been producing, this model is centered on a vertex instead of a cell. This creates a nicely symmetric model, but it also creates one vertex at infinity. The little stubby edges on the outer part of this model are all supposed to connect to one vertex at infinity.

The inner most edges on this are really thin, so I'm not sure that it would be possible to remove supports without breaking them.  I'm in the process of creating another version that has thicker edges.

When I found "trisection of a cube" by Erikjuh, I clearly wanted to design mine under openscad.
After few iterations here is the result as a customizable "twisted puzzles factory".
Just download the code and open it, you'll see how powerfull openscad is. You can, if you prefer, use the customizer to build your cube. (see instructions) I found theoritical help
  • in this very interesting paper from Carlo H. Séquin CS Division, University of California, Berkeley: Prototyping Dissection Puzzles with Layered Manufacturing (http://www.cs.berkeley.edu/~sequin/PAPERS/2012_FASE_Dissections.pdf).
  • and, of course, in G. Hart's Homepage (http://www.georgehart.com/) and screw-puzzles !

The customizer allows to modify 3 parameters:
  • the size of the cube
  • the angle you have to twist the last piece to screw it inside the other ones
  • a clearance value which is the size of the gap left between pieces
    • Don't be afraid if the displayed piece under customizer window looks uggly, The generated object will be perfect ;-) printing is easy. I made mine with PLA, sliced with slic3r, honeycomb 3D infill, 2 perimeters walls, hot end diam 0.5 mm layer height 0.2 mm.
    With an edge of 3 cm and 0.2 clearance, I had to sand the pieces. Therefore I set the default values in customizer. to a gap of 0.4mm but this will depend on the accuracy of your printer. (picture of the green cube shows an exagerated gap value of 2 mm)

A entirely printable steve model with face and pickaxe. It uses 1.75mm filament to attach the arms to the body. The v2 version is a bit more stable standing up by moving the centre of gravity of the head back. It allows the arms to be angled higher. I have created a cape for Steve! You can find it in the remixes or here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:120678

Print the parts. Attach both arms to the body with a continuous filament piece (1.75mm). The holes might need some drilling to be of the correct size. To stop them from sliding out use a soldering iron to flatten the ends of the filament so it is stopped from slipping out of the arms.
This can be done providing a fixed and a loose connection. For the fixed connection flatten the ends of the filament on both outsides of the arms. This fixes the arms rotation in relation to each other, but they can still rotate together. Also it can be sanded to give a smooth finish.
For a loose connection push one end of the filament agains to soldering iron to flatten it. Then put it through the arms and the body and attach the other end to the outside of the second arm. That way the arms can rotate individually but on one arm there will be some filament sticking out.. I recommend using a fixed connection. Angle one of the arms back a bit to counteract the pickaxe weight (like in the picture). Otherwise it will tip over.. After or before assembly you can color all the parts as you like.

Roller support blocks for first gen Jobo CPA rotary film and print processors.  
The built in roller tabs of the first gen CPA do not accommodate some shorter tanks (such as the 2820 and 2510) and also can not support the smaller 1500 series film processing tanks. These blocks use the standard Jobo rollers and can be positioned anywhere in the trough to support any length tank.  
The smaller block supports any of the 2500 or 2800 series film or paper tanks, while the taller block supports any of the 1500 series film tanks.

Slice with 100% infill so the block doesn't float.  
Print 2.  
Clean out the roller holes using a #8, 5mm or 13/64" drill bit so the roller spins smoothly.  
Clean the bottom of any printer blobs so it will fit snugly in the Jobo water trough.  
Glue the two halves together.

a revision from my previous Green Lantern's ring design. this version is more look alike the original Green Lantern's ring from the movie.

i've printed all using PLA transparent colour. i've divided the object into 3 parts so that it will be easier to print and be able to apply different colour on different parts.   
to make the ring, you need to print 1xgem.stl, 1xcrown.stl and 2xring.stl. be aware that i designed this in centimetre, the diameter of the ring is 20cm, so you need to scale it down to your own finger size.   
to colour the gem parts, i painted a green colour marker onto the transparent PLA before feed it to the printer, so that the colour get fused with the PLA during print and it become permanent. for the crown i mixed the colour with black colour marker - as in picture (resulted dark green colour).   
combine the 2 ring parts with super glue. i've painted the outer part of the gem parts using gold marker (coloured the same as the replica). the gem should be able to snap in tightly to the crown parts, you may apply some power glue to make it stay. then combine the crown and ring parts with power glue too .. now you have the green lantern's ring replica.   
as you notice there is some space gap below the gem parts, you can slide in a green 0805 SMD led that soldered to a button battery CR-1616, to make it glowing like in the last photos.   
i've included the SKP files, please feel free to edit it for adjustment purposes. and don't forget to leave comment if you like this design or if you can give me ideas on what to make next :)

title: T-Nut, for 2020 profile, printable, drop in

description.text: A "hammer-style" printable T-nut for Misumi 2020 alu profile (commonly used in MendelMax), can be inserted into the groove from the side instead of having to slide it from the end.

Print, drill out the hole to 2.5 mm, insert into the profile, screw in a M3 machine screw. The T-nut should automatically turn 90 degrees and stop. Machine screws probably won't work with ABS (too soft), but I used polycarbonate at 300 C and holding the spool arms and more seems to be no problem at all with regular M3 screws.  
Print with a brim, otherwise these will easily get knocked off by the print head.

title: RasPi camera for Tarot T2D Gimbal

description.text:
Fly RasPi camera! Fly! This is quite an advanced and yet cheap solution for aerial photography with Tarot T2D gimbals. Due to the infinite functionalities which could be implemented this is a work in progress by definition.
But right now it has many functions operational, mainly targeted to aerial Near infrared Photograpy. It has battery for atonomous operation and look! its even lighter than a Gopro! (66g instead of 80g)!
Even FPVing using the Raspi video out jack should be a breeze! (I have not yet tested this feature). My original target was interfacing a Raspberry Pi 1 Model A+ with Noir camera to the Phantom 2 Gimbal HD3D
Unfortunately this had been a failure as the DJI Jimbal is developed on purpose for the GoPro3. Even if a bit lighter, I couldn't optimize the camera's balancing (barycenter) enough to get it working.
So I shifted to the IRIS with the Tarot 2D which has much more power (and it's quite heavier as a downside) and has a very smart controller (the Pixhawk) with many cute Output pins!!! The Raspi camera in its actual configuration has the following functions:
  • battery for autonomous operation (can be used also as an independent point and shoot camera)
  • one on/off switch to turn off the power.
  • one switch between timelapse autonomous shooting and single shots
  • 1 button to take single shots
  • single shots can be activared also directly from one of the Pixhawk output PIN set for relay operation (see brown + yellow wires)
  • 1 button to shut down safely the Pi.
  • blue filter holder for near-infrared photography
  • protective cap for lens and filter
  • AV out should be available for FPV (not yet checked)
    • Iris' Pixhawk can activate the Raspi camera shutter directly using MissionPlanner hence it will let you plan aerial photography very effectively. Part list:
  • Raspberry Pi 1 Model A+ 23.75 €
  • Raspberry NoIR camera 29.99€
  • Adafruit PowerBoost 500 Basic - 5V USB Boost @ 500mA from 1.8V+ 10.95 €
    -Lithium Ion Polymer Battery - 3.7v 500mAh 7.95 $
    -2xTactile Switch Buttons (6mm slim) x 20 pack 0.5$
    -1xBreadboard-friendly SPDT Slide Switch 0.95$
    • Total approx 75 € VAT included If you download it please LIKE IT!

description.text: I've recently brought my old Model B out of semi retirement, added a PM5 monitor and RowPro software and started on a quest to get fit again. Called micpod as in tripod. The micpod is the size of a microphone in the area that fits into the microphone holder. Put the micpod where a microphone should go to have a secure place to put your camera. So a regular mic stand is not that exciting. It can only go up and down. What is exciting IMHO is when you use this with a microphone boom stand. For those unfamiliar mic booms stands are what a drummer uses to sing.   
The micpod lets you place the camera on a steady mount where a tripod can't go. Full sized cameras are out for most mic booms.  
Things that are in the weight area of microphones work great.  
You could also read/ watch your iPhone on the couch without holding it.  
You can get a closeup of your rapman while it is running and watch it from somewhere else. Out of babys reach directly above the crib might be fun too.

The micpod needs a microphone stand of some kind and a small camera  to really be useful. The hole on the bottom lends itself to pole mounting if you wanted to get above the crowd. You would also need other pieces to run the camera.  
There are a couple ways to secure the 1/4 bolt. I put the bolt in place then poured some Alumilite down the hole to secure the bolt. You could also put a nut on the bolt, send it down the hole and secure it with another nut from the top. The hole on the bottom lends itself to pole mounting if you wanted to get above the crowd. You would also need other pieces to run the camera.

description.text: Because people don't know how to abide by creative licenses, give credit, not sell for profit, compete with me on etsy.. I'm deleting all my 3D models and stamping the ones that remain. unless thingiverse starts taking legal action or starts protecting designers. This seems like the only solution. Sorry guys Please do me a favor vote for me at this instructable contest http://www.instructables.com/id/3D-printed-Tool-WristBand-w-minimal-assembly/ 3D print an entire tool wristband in one or two print jobs. No screws or much assembly required. Save your self 200-500 dollars

http://www.instructables.com/id/3D-printed-Tool-WristBand-w-minimal-assembly/ So i saw similar product on the market for 200 - 500 dollars on the internet. Not even sure is available for sale but i'm not sure if i want to drop that much money if i can make one myself. So i went to work on my computer, drafted some 3D files, 3D printed some prototypes. However, the initial prototype i printed required screws and some assembly. I could have gone to home depot and bought some screws but why should I? so maybe I could 3D print some screws and glue them in place. But it hit me.. I could 3d model the screws in place and i could 3D print the entire thing all at once. So i went back to the drawing board and 3d model the whole thing. I also placed each link in a manner that maximizes the way it prints. This method pretty much allows me to print the entire bracelet all at once. The only reason i don't print the second part of the clasp all at once because i want to print it sideways to increase strength in the direction i wanted. I think i used 50% infill or less to keep the print strong and in the lighter side. I reduced the support to the minimum but i think you can 3d print the entire thing without support but dont quote me on that. I picked the screw bits i wanted to use and had them ready for when the print comes out. So here is the trick.. You have to be there when the print finishes and it still warm. start putting the screw bits into place while it still warm and do it quick or you will have to use a heat gun This will be the easiest part but it will get a little complicated when you put the other half of the bits. Remove the bracelet from the print bed and one by one heat up the hole and insert the screw bit into place. Once you have all the screw bits into place 3D print the clasp.. and glue into place with the rest of the bracelet. if the clasp is a little too lose heat it up and squish it to make it tighter.
